    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-01-22T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-01-22T13:00:00-05:00" n="1085"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1085">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">774.56/1–2253: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 1085<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Egypt (<persName corresp="#p_CJ1"
                            type="from">Caffery</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d1085fn1">Repeated to London as telegram 585.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>
                            <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-01-22T20:00:00+02:00"
                            >January 22, 1953—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1703. I fully sympathize with my colleague’s concern over what he anticipates
                    will be British reaction to interim arms program (London’s 4001 to Department
                    repeated Cairo 212).<note n="2" xml:id="d1085fn2">
                        <ref target="#d1084">
                            <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> However, again London Foreign Office completely, misjudges
                    situation in Egypt.</p>
                <p>If after encouragement we have given <persName corresp="#p_NGM1"
                        >Naguib</persName> about arms, aid program is now scrapped, Egyptians will
                    surely lose their present perhaps exaggerated faith in us.</p>
                <pb facs="0268" n="1970" xml:id="pg_1970"/>
                <p>Foregoing merely leads up to crucial point, namely that if we destroy our
                    position in Egypt by accepting British veto (or even emasculation) of interim
                    arms program there will be no Anglo-Egypt settlement and no <gloss
                        target="#t_MEDO1">MEDO</gloss>. On the contrary, faced with impending
                    collapse, this regime will seek to expel British from Suez by force and will
                    incite revolt in Sudan.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                            </hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
